No, no, no! That's fine. Um, can you
tell me how I can find Patrick Sullivan?

227
00:14:57,800 --> 00:15:00,758
- We couldn't get that lady out.
- She weighed 500 pounds!

228
00:15:00,800 --> 00:15:03,712
- She knocked you with her skillet.
- Frying pan.

229
00:15:03,880 --> 00:15:05,632
- Patrick?
- Yeah. Ah!

230
00:15:05,800 --> 00:15:08,075
You won't believe this.
That home-wrecking lady.

231
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:09,798
...from the radio walked in here.

232
00:15:09,960 --> 00:15:11,757
- I believe you.
- Can I help you?

233
00:15:11,920 --> 00:15:14,388
- What's she doin'?
- Looking for Patrick Sullivan.

234
00:15:14,560 --> 00:15:17,358
- I was told he might be here.
- Right over there.

235
00:15:17,520 --> 00:15:19,511
- She looked over.
- What are you havin'?

236
00:15:19,680 --> 00:15:22,717
- Um, whatever he's having.
- I'll bring it right over.

237
00:15:22,880 --> 00:15:24,916
It's walkin' right this way.

238
00:15:25,080 --> 00:15:27,469
- It's takin' its coat off.
- How do you do?

239
00:15:27,640 --> 00:15:31,110
It just looked at me again.
It's comin' over here.

240
00:15:31,280 --> 00:15:34,192
It's comin' right for me.
What does it want?

241
00:15:36,360 --> 00:15:39,193
Patrick Sullivan?
You're not an easy man to find.

242
00:15:39,360 --> 00:15:42,989
- I'm Emma Lloyd.
- It thinks I'm you. Help me out.

243
00:15:43,160 --> 00:15:46,072
Hey, I, uh... I dropped my chalk.
I'm Patrick Sullivan.

244
00:15:46,240 --> 00:15:50,074
- This is my opponent, Larry Berlson.
- Oh! Mr. Sullivan. Mr. Berlson.

245
00:15:50,240 --> 00:15:52,515
How do you do?
I'm here for the oddest reason.

246
00:15:52,680 --> 00:15:54,272
- We all are.
- Here you are.

247
00:15:54,440 --> 00:15:56,237
- Mine?
- Mind if I interrupt?

248
00:15:56,400 --> 00:15:58,311
- Knock yourself out.
- I didn't mean...

249
00:15:58,480 --> 00:15:59,629
- Don't play?
- Yes.

250
00:15:59,800 --> 00:16:02,030
Then you're stripes.
Down the hatch.

251
00:16:02,200 --> 00:16:06,318
- No, no, Mr. Sullivan. I'm here to...
- You don't drink? You don't play pool?

252
00:16:06,480 --> 00:16:10,871
Perhaps I can get you an herbal tea?

253
00:16:12,560 --> 00:16:14,232
Nine in the corner.

254
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:18,991
We need another round.

255
00:16:19,160 --> 00:16:21,879
Mr. Sullivan. Something
very unfortunate has happened...

256
00:16:22,040 --> 00:16:24,952
- And it could make a mess of my life.
- I'm sorry to hear that.

257
00:16:25,120 --> 00:16:27,475
- It's certainly not your fault.
- It's your shot.

258
00:16:27,640 --> 00:16:30,677
Um, all right.
Well, how can I explain?

259
00:16:30,840 --> 00:16:34,389
You see, um, uh,
I'm about to be married.

260
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:36,437
That is too bad!

261
00:16:36,600 --> 00:16:39,831
Congratulations on the other thing.
We got a bride in our midst.

262
00:16:42,320 --> 00:16:44,470
Thank you. That won't be necessary.

263
00:16:44,640 --> 00:16:48,110
It's necessary. I feel a toast
coming on. Wait a second.

264
00:16:48,280 --> 00:16:50,350
- I know you.
- Excuse me?

265
00:16:50,520 --> 00:16:53,114
Yeah, yeah.
Real Love With Dr Emma Lloyd.

266
00:16:53,280 --> 00:16:57,114
- You're that lady I hear on the radio.
- Yes, of course. You found me out.

267
00:16:57,280 --> 00:17:00,670
- Have you ever been on television?
- Um, no, but I have a book coming out.

268
00:17:00,840 --> 00:17:03,912
- I love television.
- My girlfriend never misses your show.

269
00:17:04,080 --> 00:17:06,548
Oh, well, has it been
helpful in your relationship?

270
00:17:06,720 --> 00:17:10,679
Oh, you have no idea.
It's completely changed our lives!

271
00:17:10,840 --> 00:17:14,389
- Oh, really? That is so nice to hear.
- Yeah. Tony! Here you go.

272
00:17:14,560 --> 00:17:17,233
- To the bride and ever-changing life!
- To the bride!

273
00:17:17,400 --> 00:17:20,039
To the bride!

274
00:17:21,200 --> 00:17:25,034
Mr. Sullivan, as I was saying,
you see, I'm about to be married.

275
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:28,556
Be careful. Forty-three per cent
of marriages end in divorce.

276
00:17:28,720 --> 00:17:31,598
That's right. It's all
about picking the right partner.

277
00:17:31,760 --> 00:17:34,718
- So true. It's so true.
- In order to do that, my fiancé...

278
00:17:34,880 --> 00:17:37,110
Richard, and I,
need a license from New York...

279
00:17:37,280 --> 00:17:41,319
- Richard from dispatch? Asshole.
- So on an otherwise lovely morning...

280
00:17:41,480 --> 00:17:43,675
- we go to city hall...
- To Emma and Richie!

281
00:17:43,840 --> 00:17:46,832
Richard!

282
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:49,594
- And I don't want any more.
- Hey, you're right.

283
00:17:49,760 --> 00:17:52,593
Don't want Richie to see
you hammered before your wedding.

284
00:17:52,760 --> 00:17:54,796
Tony! Give me
that herbal tea over here.

285
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:57,758
Herbal tea, coming up!

286
00:17:57,920 --> 00:18:02,516
Very funny, Mr. Sullivan. Very funny.

287
00:18:02,680 --> 00:18:05,069
- I'll have you know I don't get drunk.
- You don't?

288
00:18:05,240 --> 00:18:08,277
No. My father taught me a good trick
to hold one's liquor.

289
00:18:08,440 --> 00:18:11,034
You simply recite
the presidents' names in order.

290
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:13,760
- Out loud?
- Forwards or backwards?

291
00:18:13,920 --> 00:18:17,310
Watch and learn, gentlemen.
To Washington, Adams, Jefferson...

292
00:18:17,480 --> 00:18:19,277
Madison and Monroe.

293
00:18:20,520 --> 00:18:22,351
- Carter!
- Carter!

294
00:18:22,520 --> 00:18:25,637
- Reagan!
- Reagan!

295
00:18:25,800 --> 00:18:27,552
- Bush!
- Bush!

296
00:18:27,720 --> 00:18:30,393
Do you think maybe we
should pour you into a cab?

297
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:32,994
- Maybe your fiancé's worried.
- Oh! That's right!

298
00:18:33,160 --> 00:18:35,549
That is exactly what
I came to talk to you about.

299
00:18:35,720 --> 00:18:37,631
- OK.
- Yes, Mr. Sullivan...

300
00:18:37,800 --> 00:18:40,075
- it seems we're married.
- Come again?

301
00:18:40,240 --> 00:18:44,028
We... Are married!

302
00:18:44,200 --> 00:18:46,714
- I thought you were marrying Richie.
- Exactly!

303
00:18:46,880 --> 00:18:48,279
- I'm over here.
- Right!

304
00:18:48,440 --> 00:18:52,718
Uh, yes, it seems that we,
I mean we...

305
00:18:52,880 --> 00:18:56,077
...are victims of a glitch in some
computer, somewhere, somehow...

306
00:18:56,240 --> 00:18:58,800
I don't know, has married us.

307
00:18:58,960 --> 00:19:02,350
- A glitch?
- Mm-hm. I'll say. A big one.

308
00:19:02,520 --> 00:19:08,038
- Oh, boy.
- So, um, if, um, you'd just be...

309
00:19:08,200 --> 00:19:11,158
...so kind as
to sign these papers I'd...

310
00:19:13,720 --> 00:19:15,870
Ow!

311
00:19:18,520 --> 00:19:21,353
Washington, Madison, Adamson...

312
00:19:21,520 --> 00:19:24,353
- Are you a fireman?
- Indeed, I am.

313
00:19:24,520 --> 00:19:26,988
I always liked you guys.

314
00:19:29,800 --> 00:19:32,155
Lights are out now.

315
00:20:04,840 --> 00:20:07,400
Sorry about that.

316
00:20:28,560 --> 00:20:30,357
Oh! Ouch!

317
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:32,992
Hello? Oh, no!

318
00:21:33,160 --> 00:21:35,799
Oh, no! Oh, no!

319
00:21:41,560 --> 00:21:44,028
Oh, my God!

320
00:21:44,200 --> 00:21:46,714
Oh, my God!

321
00:21:46,880 --> 00:21:48,393
Oh!

322
00:21:51,320 --> 00:21:53,151
Oh, my God.

323
00:22:10,720 --> 00:22:11,789
Oh!

324
00:22:19,400 --> 00:22:20,389
Excuse me.

325
00:22:27,600 --> 00:22:31,832
- Good morning, Dr Lloyd.
- Good morning. Wait!

326
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:34,036
- Someone had a rough night.
- Oh, yeah.

327
00:22:37,200 --> 00:22:39,156
Excuse me.

328
00:22:43,240 --> 00:22:46,391
- Oh, my.
- I need the emergency outfit.

329
00:22:46,560 --> 00:22:48,118
- What?
- The emergency outfit!

330
00:22:48,280 --> 00:22:49,918
Outfit I keep for emergencies.

331
00:22:50,080 --> 00:22:52,799
Richard called six and a half times.
Last time he hung up.

332
00:22:52,960 --> 00:22:55,713
He was looking desperate.
Worried about Bollenbeckers?

333
00:22:55,880 --> 00:22:57,757
- Can you get him for me?
- On the phone?

334
00:22:57,920 --> 00:22:59,672
- Why do you do that?
- It's fun.

335
00:22:59,840 --> 00:23:02,354
- The outfit?
- Not here.

336
00:23:02,520 --> 00:23:03,669
- I had a date.
- Oh!

337
00:23:03,840 --> 00:23:05,990
You know we're not remotely
the same size?

338
00:23:06,160 --> 00:23:09,357
- Richard. Aspirin. Coffee.
- Oh, and your father's...

339
00:23:09,520 --> 00:23:13,195
- Now!
- Please hold. Richard, line one!

340
00:23:16,200 --> 00:23:20,159
Richard, sweetheart.
I am so sorry I didn't call.

341
00:23:20,320 --> 00:23:24,029
I was in Queens so I thought I'd stay at
my father's and go over wedding stuff.

342
00:23:24,200 --> 00:23:26,839
- Why didn't you call?
- He brought you in this morning.

343
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:29,434
- with your mom's dress.
- He brought me back in.

344
00:23:29,600 --> 00:23:32,273
- with my mom's wedding dress.
- And your father's here.

345
00:23:32,440 --> 00:23:34,431
- She knows it.
- What about Sullivan?

346
00:23:34,600 --> 00:23:35,919
- It's beautiful.
- Emma?

347
00:23:36,080 --> 00:23:38,992
- Yes! I found Sullivan.
- Coffee, Wilder?

348
00:23:39,160 --> 00:23:40,479
- I'd love some.
- Aspirin?

349
00:23:40,640 --> 00:23:42,471
- I've got the papers.
- Welcome.

350
00:23:42,640 --> 00:23:44,153
Not on me.

351
00:23:44,320 --> 00:23:45,992
- Coffee filters?
- I don't work here.

352
00:23:46,160 --> 00:23:48,754
I know they have to be notarized.
Can you get that?

353
00:23:48,920 --> 00:23:50,399
- Sure.
- Don't worry.

354
00:23:50,560 --> 00:23:55,190
You have enough on your plate without
having to worry about this. Don't...

355
00:23:55,360 --> 00:23:57,920
Emma, your husband would
like a few words with you.

356
00:23:58,080 --> 00:23:59,877
- Who?
- Patrick Sullivan?

357
00:24:00,040 --> 00:24:02,554
...have them on you?
- Sweetheart, can you, um?...

358
00:24:02,720 --> 00:24:05,473
Can you hold please? Not a word.

359
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:08,677
Hello? You there? Hello?

360
00:24:08,840 --> 00:24:10,910
- Ah! Mr. Sullivan?
- Hey.

361
00:24:11,080 --> 00:24:14,516
Let me get to the point. I left some
very important documents in your...

362
00:24:14,680 --> 00:24:17,353
- Richard! Phone!
- Uh, can you just hold on.

363
00:24:17,520 --> 00:24:19,909
- One second? Don't go away.
- Yeah.

364
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:24,716
Richard, sweetheart,
I am so sorry to keep you holding.

365
00:24:24,880 --> 00:24:27,474
- What's going on?
- I'll explain at the cake tasting.

366
00:24:27,640 --> 00:24:31,553
- I can't. I'll meet you tonight.
- But you promised. All right.

367
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:35,554
Husband! Cell!

368
00:24:35,720 --> 00:24:39,395
Oh! Mr. Sullivan? Mr. Sullivan!

369
00:24:39,560 --> 00:24:41,551
- Wilder, here.
- Mr. Sullivan? Hello?

370
00:24:41,720 --> 00:24:44,598
- Your father on two.
- Gotta run, darling! See you later.

371
00:24:44,760 --> 00:24:47,877
- Gonna wait for your coffee?
- Nobody's got that kind of time.

372
00:24:48,040 --> 00:24:50,759
I don't know what
you're smirking about, Wilder.

373
00:24:50,920 --> 00:24:53,070
I'm just glad
to see you're having some fun.

374
00:24:53,240 --> 00:24:56,073
Does it look like I'm having fun?
Wait.

375
00:24:56,240 --> 00:24:59,915
You drove all the way in
just to bring Mom's dress?

376
00:25:00,080 --> 00:25:03,231
Actually, I was hoping
to lure you over to Bemelmans.

377
00:25:03,400 --> 00:25:07,439
- For a banana split like the old days.
- Bemelmans has been closed for years.

378
00:25:07,600 --> 00:25:10,512
Ah, well, my timing's
always been a little off.

379
00:25:10,680 --> 00:25:13,319
Don't keep your husbands waiting.

380
00:25:13,480 --> 00:25:16,153
- It's not what you think.
- I know.

381
00:25:16,320 --> 00:25:19,357
Mr. Sullivan?
Thank you so much for calling back.

382
00:25:19,520 --> 00:25:21,317
- Excuse me?
- What do you want?

383
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:24,040
- Car's downstairs. You're late.
- Mr. Sullivan.

384
00:25:24,200 --> 00:25:26,236
- Yes.
- Yes, about last night.

385
00:25:26,400 --> 00:25:27,958
- Yeah.
- What exactly happened?

386
00:25:28,120 --> 00:25:31,874
I tell you this, you do one hell
of a Riverdance. It was quite a night.

387
00:25:32,040 --> 00:25:34,759
- That doesn't sound like me.
- That wasn't the good part.

388
00:25:34,920 --> 00:25:36,399
- What do you mean?
- I'm here.

389
00:25:36,560 --> 00:25:40,189
You're where?
Hey, I'm losing you. Hello?

390
00:25:40,360 --> 00:25:42,999
Can you hear me now?
Look, forget last night.

391
00:25:43,160 --> 00:25:46,118
What I want is a rather large stack
of papers I need you to sign.

392
00:25:46,280 --> 00:25:49,238
- I got 'em right here.
- You do! Thanks. You made my day.

393
00:25:49,400 --> 00:25:51,755
- Coffee?
- Thank you.

394
00:25:51,920 --> 00:25:54,718
- I know a notary not far from here.
- Right now?

395
00:25:54,880 --> 00:25:57,110
This appointment
took me three months to get.

396
00:25:57,280 --> 00:25:59,111
- Sounds important.
- Cake tasting.

397
00:25:59,280 --> 00:26:01,919
- Like I said, important stuff.
- It's the wedding cake...

398
00:26:02,080 --> 00:26:04,878
...and she's Marilyn Hirschfield,
a respected cake maker.

399
00:26:05,040 --> 00:26:07,395
- These appointments are hard...
- I love cake!

400
00:26:07,560 --> 00:26:09,596
- What are you doing? Hey!
- Scoot over.

401
00:26:09,760 --> 00:26:13,992
- This cake is fantastic!
- Shh! Please, please. Be quiet.

402
00:26:14,160 --> 00:26:17,835
- Can I get another slice of this one?
- You've already tried the butter cream.

403
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:21,117
It's my fiancée. She's on the fence
about the butter cream.

404
00:26:21,280 --> 00:26:22,838
- I am not.
- Have any milk?

405
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:24,956
- Sure.
- After this, we go to the notary?

406
00:26:25,120 --> 00:26:28,476
- Yeah, absolutely. How much is this?
- It's free, sir.

407
00:26:28,640 --> 00:26:31,871
Bullshit! It's free!

408
00:26:32,040 --> 00:26:35,077
- Here you are, sir.
- Here's my milk.

409
00:26:35,240 --> 00:26:38,915
- Would you like a sip?
- No, thank you. I'm not six.

410
00:26:39,080 --> 00:26:41,310
Holy crap! Cake down.

411
00:26:41,480 --> 00:26:44,313
I need a spoon. Don't worry about it.
I got this.

412
00:26:44,480 --> 00:26:48,029
Here we have our dark Belgian chocolate
with vanilla mousse torte.

413
00:26:48,200 --> 00:26:50,031
- Thank you.
- It's awesome.

414
00:26:54,680 --> 00:26:57,478
Oh, my God! Do you know
if you mix these two together...

415
00:26:57,640 --> 00:26:59,915
...it tastes like a Ring Ding!
You gotta try this.

416
00:27:00,080 --> 00:27:04,039
No, no, no. That's all right.
I'm not your baby. No, no, no, no, no!

417
00:27:04,200 --> 00:27:06,111
- Ah! Ah!
- No!

418
00:27:06,280 --> 00:27:07,713
- Mmm?
- Ah?

419
00:27:07,880 --> 00:27:12,078
- Mm. It's yummy.
- It's super-duper.

420
00:27:12,240 --> 00:27:16,916
Mm-hm. Um, may I, um... May I just
have one more glass of milk, please?

421
00:27:17,080 --> 00:27:19,878
Attagirl! Milk for my bride.
In fact, milks all around.

422
00:27:20,040 --> 00:27:21,712
Milks all around.

423
00:27:21,880 --> 00:27:24,678
- Hey, where you ladies from?
- Germany.

424
00:27:24,840 --> 00:27:26,751
Wow! You must really like cake.

425
00:27:26,920 --> 00:27:29,718
Yeah, you gotta try this,
and mix these two together.

426
00:27:29,880 --> 00:27:33,395
Hey, hey, can we get, uh, some
Ring Ding things for the gals over here?

427
00:27:33,560 --> 00:27:36,028
Darling, I am certain
everyone is being attended to.

428
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:39,078
Baby, I got this covered.
Don't you worry about it.

429
00:27:39,240 --> 00:27:42,152
- Quite a handful you got there.
- That he is.

430
00:27:42,320 --> 00:27:46,233
Impulsive, unpredictable. You never
know what he's gonna do next.

431
00:27:46,400 --> 00:27:49,437
- Full of surprises.
- But that's the fun of it, isn't it?

432
00:27:49,600 --> 00:27:52,797
- Of course it is.
- It is, trust me.

433
00:27:52,960 --> 00:27:55,633
- Here you go, ladies.
- He reminds me of my husband.

434
00:27:55,800 --> 00:27:59,031
when we first met. Everybody
thought we were a total mismatch...

435
00:27:59,200 --> 00:28:03,990
...but we had so much fun.
And we still do 25 years later.

436
00:28:04,160 --> 00:28:06,799
Hey! What are you ladies
talkin' about over here?

437
00:28:06,960 --> 00:28:09,315
- Talking about the men in our lives.
- Ah, boys.

438
00:28:09,480 --> 00:28:12,631
- Never mind.
- How did you two meet?

439
00:28:14,240 --> 00:28:17,516
Oh, honey, you tell the story.
You tell it a lot better than I do.

440
00:28:17,680 --> 00:28:23,312
No, no, no, no, no. No, you tell it.
You're the good, uh, teller of it.

441
00:28:23,480 --> 00:28:25,675
- Please?
- All right, all right. Sure.

442
00:28:25,840 --> 00:28:29,549
- You ladies heard of pro wrestling?
- Stop! Kidder!

443
00:28:29,720 --> 00:28:31,597
Oh, he's such a kidder. Kidder.

444
00:28:31,760 --> 00:28:34,752
It was a, um, uh... A blind date.

445
00:28:34,920 --> 00:28:37,354
- Oh?
- Yeah, yeah, we were fixed up.

446
00:28:37,520 --> 00:28:39,875
Yes! Fixed up.
But not with each other.

447
00:28:40,040 --> 00:28:43,191
It was two separate blind dates
in the same bar.

448
00:28:43,360 --> 00:28:45,191
- Both goin' terribly.
- Horribly!

449
00:28:45,360 --> 00:28:47,430
Think about those people who set us up.

450
00:28:47,600 --> 00:28:49,636
- Susie and Allen.
- Susie and Allen.

451
00:28:49,800 --> 00:28:53,713
- What the hell did they know?
- I don't know. I guess he noticed me.

452
00:28:53,880 --> 00:28:56,997
Well, I mean, come on. Look at her.

453
00:28:57,160 --> 00:29:02,154
- A guy would have to be blind.
- Noticed me suffering on my bad date...

454
00:29:02,320 --> 00:29:06,472
...and then the band started playing this
song, and it was my favorite song.

455
00:29:06,640 --> 00:29:11,794
And suddenly he was next to me and
he asked me to dance, and... I said yes.

456
00:29:14,240 --> 00:29:16,276
- What was the song?
- Song?

457
00:29:16,440 --> 00:29:19,273
- Mm-hm?
- Oh, yeah, the song.

458
00:29:19,440 --> 00:29:21,874
- Oh.
- # Over night scenes.

459
00:29:22,040 --> 00:29:25,191
# Dinner and wine
Saturday girls.

460
00:29:25,360 --> 00:29:28,477
# I was never in love
Never had the time.

461
00:29:28,640 --> 00:29:31,950
- Honey, Every Woman in the World.
- Every Woman in the World.

462
00:29:32,120 --> 00:29:34,270
# Laughing myself to sleep.

463
00:29:34,440 --> 00:29:38,479
# Waking up lonely
I needed someone to hold me.

464
00:29:38,640 --> 00:29:39,709
# Oh, oh, oh.

465
00:29:39,880 --> 00:29:44,908
# Girl, you're every woman
in the world to me.

466
00:29:45,080 --> 00:29:47,719
# You're my fantasy.

467
00:29:47,880 --> 00:29:51,953
- # You're my reality
- That's it! Uh, that's the song.

468
00:29:59,120 --> 00:30:01,076
That was totally
off the top of my head.

469
00:30:01,240 --> 00:30:04,949
Known each other for two hours
and we already got a song.

470
00:30:05,120 --> 00:30:09,477
We don't have a song.
How long is this gonna take?

471
00:30:18,680 --> 00:30:21,148
Emma Lloyd, Deepak Manaam Chaturvedi.

472
00:30:21,320 --> 00:30:23,515
- Mr. Manaam Chater...
- Deep. Deep.

473
00:30:23,680 --> 00:30:25,398
- Mr. Deep.
- I recognize you.

474
00:30:25,560 --> 00:30:27,835
The passed-out lady
Patrick carries around.

475
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:29,718
Yes, that would be me.

476
00:30:31,320 --> 00:30:34,517
- I brought you a little something.
- Oh, how very thoughtful.

477
00:30:35,640 --> 00:30:37,631
Do we have to do this right now?

478
00:30:40,080 --> 00:30:41,593
Delicious.

479
00:30:41,760 --> 00:30:44,069
- It's not unlike a Ring Ding.
- What'd I tell you?

480
00:30:44,240 --> 00:30:46,754
I'm sure you'd really love
a glass of milk with that...

481
00:30:46,920 --> 00:30:49,354
...but I have to get home
and changed for my book party.

482
00:30:49,520 --> 00:30:52,193
- If you don't mind...
- Don't rush. I'm a notary public.

483
00:30:52,360 --> 00:30:54,715
- I took a test.
- OK, I'm sorry.

484
00:30:54,880 --> 00:30:57,269
Um, how long do you
think this will take?

485
00:30:57,440 --> 00:30:59,271
Let's just review, hm?

486
00:31:00,360 --> 00:31:03,796
Signatures... Check.

487
00:31:03,960 --> 00:31:08,431
Dates... Check.

488
00:31:08,600 --> 00:31:11,068
My seal and you'll be
on your way in ten minutes.

489
00:31:11,240 --> 00:31:13,356
- Oh!
- An hour.

490
00:31:14,440 --> 00:31:16,351
A year.

491
00:31:16,520 --> 00:31:18,317
As long as it takes.
Who can say?

492
00:31:18,480 --> 00:31:21,358
Anything you can do to hurry?
I don't mind paying extra.

493
00:31:21,520 --> 00:31:25,877
- Trying to bribe a public official?
- Oh, this is ridiculous. I'm late!

494
00:31:26,040 --> 00:31:28,759
I'm late, and I'll send
a messenger in the morning.

495
00:31:28,920 --> 00:31:31,070
That will be more than enough time.

496
00:31:31,240 --> 00:31:34,277
- I could bring it by the office.
- Oh, no. I will send a messenger.

497
00:31:34,440 --> 00:31:37,273
Thank you, Mr. Sullivan,
for your co-operation.

498
00:31:37,440 --> 00:31:40,352
Well, thank you for thanking me,
Mrs. Sullivan.

499
00:31:41,480 --> 00:31:43,118
- A year?
- Patrick, I'm out. Out.

500
00:31:43,280 --> 00:31:45,953
You had your fun. This is too far.
You should be ashamed.

501
00:31:46,120 --> 00:31:48,873
- A nice lady like that?
- I wanted to give her a taste.

502
00:31:49,040 --> 00:31:53,033
...of her own medicine, period.
And then I... I don't know.

503
00:31:53,200 --> 00:31:56,954
- She's starting to grow on me.
- No. Look, no growing, OK?

504
00:31:57,120 --> 00:32:00,874
No growing on anyone by anyone.
No knees weakened...

505
00:32:01,040 --> 00:32:05,989
...no shines taken to, none of it.
Not on my watch.

506
00:32:06,160 --> 00:32:10,472
Now, go. You and Ajay
have caused enough trouble.

507
00:32:11,600 --> 00:32:12,919
Out!

508
00:32:13,080 --> 00:32:15,071
Dr Lloyd! This way, please!

509
00:32:15,240 --> 00:32:17,993
Dr Lloyd? This camera, please.

510
00:32:18,160 --> 00:32:21,391
- Smile, please.
- Beautiful, thank you.

511
00:32:21,560 --> 00:32:24,358
- Hi.
- Eye contact, please?

512
00:32:24,520 --> 00:32:28,593
- Sign this.
- This way, please.

513
00:32:28,760 --> 00:32:31,069
- And where's Richard?
- Right over there.

514
00:32:31,240 --> 00:32:32,719
Thanks.

515
00:32:33,640 --> 00:32:35,596
- Hi! Oh!
- Not too shabby, huh?

516
00:32:35,760 --> 00:32:38,433
- It's wonderful. I can't believe it.
- Sign these.

517
00:32:38,600 --> 00:32:39,669
OK.

518
00:32:40,600 --> 00:32:43,194
- I have so much to tell you.
- Did you get the papers?

519
00:32:43,360 --> 00:32:47,035
- Um, they're at the notary.
- Excellent. Karl Bollenbecker's here.

520
00:32:47,200 --> 00:32:48,474
- Make that out to him.
- Oh?

521
00:32:48,640 --> 00:32:51,552
He wasn't coming, then his
office said he was. Good or bad?

522
00:32:51,720 --> 00:32:53,950
How could it be bad?
He hasn't even met you.

523
00:32:54,120 --> 00:32:56,156
- You look stunning.
- Thanks.

524
00:32:56,320 --> 00:32:58,754
- What happened to your head?
- Oh! Bird accident.

525
00:32:58,920 --> 00:33:01,753
A pigeon flew into me.
I'll go take care of it.

526
00:33:03,600 --> 00:33:07,309
- Emma? You remember Dr Benton?
- Yes, hi. Nice to see you. Hi, Judy.

527
00:33:13,360 --> 00:33:17,558
No sooner do we leave you then, bang,
I see your picture big on the bus.

528
00:33:17,720 --> 00:33:19,597
Oh! From the cake tasting!

529
00:33:19,760 --> 00:33:23,435
I felt so foolish, I went
and bought your book immediately.

530
00:33:23,600 --> 00:33:25,875
- Oh, that's unnecessary.
- Later I was reading.

531
00:33:26,040 --> 00:33:30,079
...your very sensible observation
and your clinical judgments...

532
00:33:30,240 --> 00:33:33,835
- Are they good things?
- I'm sure some people find them useful...

533
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:37,754
...but I was surprised that a helpless
romantic can give such practical advice.

534
00:33:37,920 --> 00:33:40,798
- Me? Helpless?
- Oh, yes, you.

535
00:33:40,960 --> 00:33:43,269
Hopelessly helpless,
but let me finish.

536
00:33:43,440 --> 00:33:47,752
So my husband, Karl, returns
to the home and on top of his paper...

537
00:33:47,920 --> 00:33:52,675
...there is an invitation to this
very party. Isn't it amazing?

538
00:33:52,840 --> 00:33:54,956
When you say Karl,
do you mean Karl...

539
00:33:55,120 --> 00:33:56,758
Bollenbecker.

540
00:33:56,920 --> 00:34:00,549
- It's a small world, isn't it?
- Yes!

541
00:34:00,720 --> 00:34:04,508
Teeny. Like a marble.
Or a gumball.

542
00:34:04,680 --> 00:34:07,274
I had to drag Karl
by the ear to come here.

543
00:34:07,440 --> 00:34:09,635
- It is a girly book.
- Oh, no. It's not that.

544
00:34:09,800 --> 00:34:13,509
Karl can be very girly. Only that he
doesn't like to socialize with someone.

545
00:34:13,680 --> 00:34:18,390
- whose company he intends to liquidate.
- Liquidate?

546
00:34:18,560 --> 00:34:21,950
- Who, Richard?
- Yes, but we can fix that.

547
00:34:22,120 --> 00:34:25,795
After this party, you and Richard
will join us for dinner.

548
00:34:25,960 --> 00:34:31,114
If Karl sees the man I saw,
Abdington Books will be safe, I'm sure.

549
00:34:31,280 --> 00:34:35,353
That is unbelievably kind of you...

550
00:34:35,520 --> 00:34:38,717
...but you see, Richard and I made plans
and so we're supposed to...

551
00:34:38,880 --> 00:34:41,030
Only one thing
you're supposed to do, Emma...

552
00:34:41,200 --> 00:34:45,910
...and it's to bring your fiancé to dinner.
Let's find Richard. Karl is waiting.

553
00:34:50,520 --> 00:34:54,433
Oh! Oh, oh, my husband hates you,
but you saved our marriage. Do you mind?

554
00:34:54,600 --> 00:34:56,591
Not at all.
Um, who shall I make it out to?

555
00:34:56,760 --> 00:34:58,193
- To...
- Richard!

556
00:35:01,760 --> 00:35:05,116
Um... Thank you.

557
00:35:06,280 --> 00:35:08,271
Oh, hey, hey.
I brought your papers.

558
00:35:08,440 --> 00:35:12,592
Richard! Sweetheart.
Please go with me on this, OK?

559
00:35:12,760 --> 00:35:14,955
- Remember Greta Bollenbecker?
- Cake lady!

560
00:35:15,120 --> 00:35:19,318
- It's a small world.
- So small. Constantly shrinking.

561
00:35:19,480 --> 00:35:22,119
- It must be the global warming.
- I want to introduce you.

562
00:35:22,280 --> 00:35:24,669
- To my husband.
- Her husband, Karl...

563
00:35:24,840 --> 00:35:27,559
...is Karl Bollenbecker,
who just acquired Richard's...

564
00:35:27,720 --> 00:35:31,269
...your publishing house and he's thinking
of dumping you, Richard, and it.

565
00:35:31,440 --> 00:35:34,512
- Wait, I own a publishing house?
- Yes, and you're my fiancé...

566
00:35:34,680 --> 00:35:37,877
...so please just focus, concentrate.
Got it?

567
00:35:38,040 --> 00:35:40,474
This is him.

568
00:35:40,640 --> 00:35:43,598
- You must be the cake dunker.
- You got me.

569
00:35:43,760 --> 00:35:47,878
- That's my Richard!
- Casual Fridays?

570
00:35:48,040 --> 00:35:50,190
I actually just came
from soccer practice.

571
00:35:50,360 --> 00:35:53,238
- You play football?
- Well, I'm no Lucas Podolski.

572
00:35:53,400 --> 00:35:56,551
Podolski!
Well, nothing could beat Podolski!

573
00:35:56,720 --> 00:36:00,838
I own his team and he is a magnificent
pain in the ass, but a genius.

574
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:03,275
You own the Bayern München club?

575
00:36:03,440 --> 00:36:06,671
Why don't you use Klose on defense?
He's been under-utilized.

576
00:36:06,840 --> 00:36:09,877
- That's what I told that stupid coach.
- Klinsmann? Gotta go.

577
00:36:10,040 --> 00:36:13,396
- We agree.
- Excuse me. My name's... Ow! Jesus!

578
00:36:13,560 --> 00:36:15,118
- What?...
- Hand noogies!

579
00:36:15,280 --> 00:36:19,796
We give each other hand noogies.
This is my brother, Carl.

580
00:36:19,960 --> 00:36:22,952
Your name is Carl as well?
This is a small world!

581
00:36:23,120 --> 00:36:27,477
Yes, teeny! Like a gimlet. Yes, my tiny,
teeny little brother, but not small.

582
00:36:27,640 --> 00:36:30,791
No. Big. Older, but not by much.

583
00:36:30,960 --> 00:36:34,555
- Carl, who I love so very, very much.
- How's it goin', bro?

584
00:36:34,720 --> 00:36:38,633
- Wine?
- I'm sorry, I'm suddenly very thirsty.

585
00:36:38,800 --> 00:36:42,031
- Carl? Carl?
- Carl.

586
00:36:42,200 --> 00:36:44,953
This is Karl Bollenbecker
and I'm Greta, his wife...

587
00:36:45,120 --> 00:36:49,830
- And we're so charmed by your sister.
- And her outspoken fiancé

588
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:53,197
who seems to find fault with
every player in the Bundesliga.

589
00:36:53,360 --> 00:36:57,273
- But not Podolski.
- But never Podolski!

590
00:36:58,600 --> 00:37:01,068
So, you sound English,
but your sister...

591
00:37:01,240 --> 00:37:04,596
- Can I borrow Emma?
- Yes, but we both had... I'm sorry.

592
00:37:04,760 --> 00:37:07,957
A hand noogie!

593
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:11,150
Who is that man out there
pretending to be me?

594
00:37:11,320 --> 00:37:13,390
- I can explain.
- He's wearing sweatpants.

595
00:37:13,560 --> 00:37:16,393
- Sullivan! Honey, you're stress-eating.
- I'm not. Go on.

596
00:37:16,560 --> 00:37:19,836
I wasn't at my father's. I was with
Sullivan. Not "with him" with him...

597
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:24,073
...but in his apartment drunk. That sounds
worse. I assure you I was fully clothed.

598
00:37:24,240 --> 00:37:26,913
Beyond that, I'm not certain,
except he showed up today.

599
00:37:27,080 --> 00:37:29,116
with papers when I had
to go to the tasting...

600
00:37:29,280 --> 00:37:31,510
which you refused to go
because you're busy...

601
00:37:31,680 --> 00:37:34,274
- Get back to the Bollenbeckers!
- Right. Fine.

602
00:37:34,440 --> 00:37:37,352
At the cake tasting,
there was this sweet lady.

603
00:37:37,520 --> 00:37:41,957
And she thought Sullivan was my fiancé
and I just couldn't disappoint her.

604
00:37:42,120 --> 00:37:45,749
But this lady wasn't sweet at all.
She was Mrs. Bollenbecker...

605
00:37:45,920 --> 00:37:48,229
- which I didn't know.
- You certainly know now!

606
00:37:48,400 --> 00:37:51,472
I do. Had I known I wouldn't
have let the whole thing continue.

607
00:37:51,640 --> 00:37:54,791
But it did continue until everyone
was quite taken with him...

608
00:37:54,960 --> 00:37:57,599
...especially Mrs. Bollenbecker
when he sang.

609
00:37:57,760 --> 00:38:00,069
- He's a singer?
- No, no, no. He's a fireman.

610
00:38:00,240 --> 00:38:05,360
- Darling, are you sure you want that?
- Yes. Yes, I am. What is he doing here?

611
00:38:05,520 --> 00:38:07,988
He came to bring me
the notarized papers.

612
00:38:08,160 --> 00:38:12,676
But then there was Mrs. Bollenbecker.
I'm Emma Lloyd, so he's my fiancé.

613
00:38:12,840 --> 00:38:17,277
- And I am tiny brother Carl.
- Oh, Richard, I'm terribly sorry.

614
00:38:17,440 --> 00:38:20,591
But, uh, oh, look! Mini-cupcakes.

615
00:38:20,760 --> 00:38:23,479
Look, Emma. I only got
about half of what you're saying...

616
00:38:23,640 --> 00:38:26,518
...but this seems to be something
that can be cleaned up easily.

617
00:38:26,680 --> 00:38:30,309
So before you harpoon what is left of my
reputation, I am gonna go in there...

618
00:38:30,480 --> 00:38:33,199
No, no, no, you can't!
They're going to exterminate you.

619
00:38:33,360 --> 00:38:35,999
- What?
- Not you, Abdington Books.

620
00:38:36,160 --> 00:38:39,596
Terminate! No, liquidate! That's it.
Yes, chop it up in little pieces...

621
00:38:39,760 --> 00:38:43,469
...sell it all off! Everything must go!
That's why Karl wasn't coming.

622
00:38:43,640 --> 00:38:45,995
- But he did come!
- Because Mrs. B made him come.

623
00:38:46,160 --> 00:38:48,628
She made him come so he could meet you.

624
00:38:48,800 --> 00:38:52,952
Oh, look. I think he's
really starting to like you.

625
00:38:53,120 --> 00:38:55,680
Oh, all right, I...
Let me think now.

626
00:38:55,840 --> 00:38:58,991
Man owns so many entities, I can buy
a year before our paths cross...

627
00:38:59,160 --> 00:39:01,913
...so we just have to get through this.
A few more minutes?

628
00:39:02,080 --> 00:39:06,915
And a dinner. Tonight. It was Mrs. B's
idea, so Karl could get to know you.

629
00:39:07,080 --> 00:39:08,354
- He's gone.
- Karl?

630
00:39:08,520 --> 00:39:10,636
- No, Sullivan. He's gone.
- But the dinner!

631
00:39:10,800 --> 00:39:14,713
- Get him there!
- Oh, uh...

632
00:39:18,080 --> 00:39:20,958
- Is Sullivan even in here?
- I don't see how he'd fit.

633
00:39:21,120 --> 00:39:23,190
Not now, Marcy.

634
00:39:25,720 --> 00:39:28,439
- Find the lioness within.
- Now, you've read my book?

635
00:39:28,600 --> 00:39:32,195
Mr. Sullivan, Emma Lloyd here.

636
00:39:32,360 --> 00:39:33,429
Here's the deal.

637
00:39:33,600 --> 00:39:38,799
My entire career, and my marriage to
Richard, probably, are at stake here.

638
00:39:40,440 --> 00:39:45,230
Frankly, I need you.
I really need you... Tonight.

639
00:40:01,920 --> 00:40:04,150
- Hello?
- Say "yes" if he's there...

640
00:40:04,320 --> 00:40:07,039
- "Oh, my God" if he's not.
- Oh, my God.

641
00:40:07,200 --> 00:40:09,555
- Oh, my God!
- Don't overdo it.

642
00:40:09,720 --> 00:40:12,393
- You got hit by a cab?
- Good, nice touch.

643
00:40:12,560 --> 00:40:17,031
What hospital are you in? I'll be
right there. He was hit by a cab!

644
00:40:17,200 --> 00:40:21,273
- Who was hit by a cab?
- Is that Sullivan?

645
00:40:21,440 --> 00:40:26,070
Oh! So it was only your foot?
And you're fine, promise?

646
00:40:26,240 --> 00:40:28,196
Oh!

647
00:40:28,360 --> 00:40:32,751
Carl, he got...
a cab ran over his foot Yeah.

648
00:40:32,920 --> 00:40:36,674
- Carl can't catch a break.
- Drink lots of cocoa. Bye-bye, darling!

649
00:40:36,840 --> 00:40:41,868
Richard, I was beginning to think a man
who would leave his fiancée un-attended.

650
00:40:42,040 --> 00:40:46,113
...for so long might not be
as charming as I imagined.

651
00:40:46,280 --> 00:40:51,274
But, no matter.
Please, join us for dessert.

652
00:40:51,440 --> 00:40:54,955
Karl, I know how important
this dinner is to my future.

653
00:40:55,120 --> 00:40:57,395
with the Bollenbecker Group...

654
00:40:57,560 --> 00:41:00,358
...but I've got this family thing.

655
00:41:00,520 --> 00:41:03,432
And where I come from,
family comes first.

656
00:41:03,600 --> 00:41:07,149
So I'm just here
to invite you to a party.

657
00:41:09,560 --> 00:41:13,599
- Could be a lot of fun.
- To family! Above all else!

658
00:41:13,760 --> 00:41:15,751
To family!

659
00:41:40,720 --> 00:41:42,472
You look beautiful.

660
00:41:47,400 --> 00:41:50,039
Nice crowd for your upanayanam, man.

661
00:41:52,360 --> 00:41:55,318
- What's with all the white people?
- Party crashers.

662
00:41:55,480 --> 00:41:59,632
- Even that one?
- No, that one's with me.

663
00:41:59,800 --> 00:42:02,189
Welcome, Emma.

664
00:42:02,360 --> 00:42:03,759
Get up there.

665
00:42:54,640 --> 00:42:58,189
Oh, I love my husband
but he snores at night...

666
00:42:58,360 --> 00:43:00,396
...and it only gets worse...

667
00:43:01,600 --> 00:43:04,068
My husband snores all the time.
I just, tight slap.

668
00:43:04,240 --> 00:43:07,471
- Tight slap.
- You look really cute.

669
00:43:07,640 --> 00:43:11,872
- Why do they snore?
- Check your mehndi for hidden messages.

670
00:43:13,240 --> 00:43:16,073
It's part of the tradition.
When marriages were arranged...

671
00:43:16,240 --> 00:43:20,950
...the groom would search his bride's body
on their wedding night to find initials.

672
00:43:21,120 --> 00:43:23,111
Ah! That's naughty.

673
00:44:44,880 --> 00:44:48,350
- Did I happen to say thank you?
